AWS Containers 

? What is docker = an application that helps  manage , ship , scale and develop you apps in containers 

- Docker engine = portable , lightweight app runtime + packaging tool - responsible for creating containers based off instructions in docker file and images 

- Docker Hub = cloud service (an App Store for images) for sharing applications & automating workflows 

Containers on AWS - 

* docker used to build and AWS used to run and manage the containers on scale *

AWS provides a service to run and manage these containers at scale with : 

- ECS = AWS managed container orchestration 
- EKS = Managed Kubernetes ( more control ) 
- Fargate = serverless option (no EC2 management) 

Use cases of docker on AWS include : 

Microservices = breaking up apps into smaller services 
- Each service runs on it’s own docker container and ECS/EKS used to orchestrate + manage 

Scaling apps = i.e need to handle more traffic 
- AWS can spin up more containers from your docker image using ECS to scale more easily 

CI/CD = continuous integration / continuous deployment 
- Build docker image once and ci/cd pipelines can consistently deploy it on AWS



Docker on an Operating System ( OS )

→ Within a EC2 instance ( virtual machine on the cloud ) you can download docker on that instance 
→ You can now spin up containers that live on top of that instance that share the HOST OS ( EC2 instances OS ) 
→ Multiple Containers also share other resources like CPU and Memory from the HOST ( EC2 ) 
→ Each container might hold a seperate app like a java service / mysql db but are isolated 


Where are docker images stored in AWS ?

Docker images are stored in registries where they can be pushed and pulled from 

Registries include : 

Docker hub →  public repo where you can pull & push images + find base images like mysql

AWS ECR elastic container registry →  Cloud registry where you can store images in public / private repos


What are the differences between Docker and Virtual machines ?

VM’s : virtualises hardware 
- Run full guest OS with allocated resources from physical machine - managed by the hypervisor 
- Heavier + slow to start due to emulating full hardware + uses more resources 
- Good for running multiple OS on the same physical system 

Containers: virtualises OS 
- Lightweight , fast  and can run multiple containers than vm’s 
- Runs docker image (snapshot) of app + share host OS kernel = so less resource heavy 
- Fewer resources used vs VM’s
- Good for deploying apps in a consistent environment and way on different physical machines 
- Can be used on an OS that supports docker 


Docker file → docker build -> docker run ( container ) 
          Pull and push →  Docker hub/ Amazon ECR 


What are the container related services on AWS ? 

Amazon Elastic container Service ( ECS )  →  amazon container orchestration 
→  lets you manage containers without orchestration software 

Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service ( EKS ) →  managed Kubernetes service 
→ offers a way to use w/out managing the control plane yourself 
+ can use k8 features like LB, scaling while AWS manages the k8 control plane 

Amazon Fargate →  Amazon own server less container platform 
→ removes the need to manage underlying infra for your servers / EC2 instances 
→  define task & fargate provisions infra automatically 
→  works with ECS & EKS 

Amazon ECR → container registry 
→  cloud based registry where you can push and pull docker images to 
→  can store your images into a private / public repo 
→  private by default 


AWS Fargate vs AWS ECS  ? 

Cluster = grouping of resources like EC2’s ( servers ) 

ECS → instead of managing individual containers manually across multiple EC2’s , ECS manages those containers across multiple EC2’s within a cluster of them for example 
* ECS on EC2 when you want more control - I.e - cost , customise , integration with other aws services 

Fargate → manages all the infrastructure and you just specify what containers you want to run 
* AWS Fargate when you want no server management


AWS ECS - EC2 launch type 

1. Provision and spin up ec2 instance with your custom configuration 
2. Run the ECS AGENT on each EC2 instance = this registers your EC2 into the ECS CLUSTER 
3. You define task - means choose which containers to run 
4. ECS will then decide which EC2 instance will run specific containers and start/stopping them if needed


AWS ECS - Fargate launch type 

1. Define task definition ( blueprint ) for which container images you want to run - memory , cpu etc 
2. Choose fargate launch type 
3. Create service / stand alone task 
4. ECS provisions the compute and manages those containers + scales up and down when needed 


AWS ECS - IAM roles for ECS 

EC2 instance profile ( EC2 launch type only ) 
→ used by ECS AGENT to do it’s job and do tasks like : 
- make API calls to ECS , 
- send container logs to cloud watch logs 
- pull docker images from ECR , access secrets etc

ECS Task role 
- Allows task ( container ) to have a role 
- Different roles for different ECS services you run 
- Task role is defined in the task definition 


ECS - load balancing integrations 

In ECS you have a load balancer that sits in front of your containers = spreads traffic evenly towards healthy containers 

Application Load balancer - operates at application level @ OSI model  (POPULAR)
→ if you need HTTP/HTTPS routing ( like hostnames /paths )

Network Load balancer - operates at network level @ OSI model 
→ if you need ultra fast UDP / TCP traffic 
- High performance use cases / to pair with AWS private link 


Classic load balancer - older simpler version for legacy systems 
→ can handle  HTTP/HTTPS routing + UDP / TCP traffic  
- Supported by not recommended + no AWS FARGATE 


What is ECS auto scaling ?

To scale within ECS you have to use AWS APPLICATION AUTO SCALING 

AWS application Auto Scaling
V
ECS service auto scaling ( task / container level )
V
EC2 auto scaling ( EC2 level ) 

Target tracking - uses cloudwatch metrics ( memory , cpu ) to keep TASK / EC2 INSTANCES balanced 
Step scaling - Cloudwatch alarms triggers adding / removing TASK/ EC2 INSTANCES in steps 
Scheduled scaling - Cloudwatch scheduled actions to chance TASK / EC2 INSTANCE COUNT at specific times 
